summary: David Tennant does a podcast with Catherine Tate
title: David Tennant does a podcast with Catherine Tate
body:
1. On the new era of Doctor Who: I don’t know that I would have ever necessarily seen a whole episode. I heard it was coming back or it’s come back with Russell T. Davies and Chris Eccleston. So obviously it’s a massive big deal. So I turn on and its the episode about where Rose is a baby. So everything now set back at the 80s. This is my introduction to the new re branded Doctor Who and I’m looking and; ‘Well, it’s absolutely shocking. Like the production values haven’t changed at all.’ This is how I remember it. It’s been set as a period piece. They’ve dug up the old costumes. A fundamental misunderstanding and I just didn’t bother watching it anymore. I remember thinking: ‘This is absolutely appalling. It looks exactly like when I watched when I was a kid and didn’t think anything more about it until you came on.’ 
  2. On David Tennant’s Doctor and her casting: I didn’t watch it but I knew you were on it and I knew that I thought you were great and then I got a call to say: ‘Would you be in this episode?’ And I said…I didn’t read it or anything, I didn't’ know what the part was, anything like that, I said; Absolutely, I’d love to.’
  3. On the first Donna script: Cause I like to open stuff in the middle and just see… open it up when I first get a script and remember that bit that I just read so when I get to film it I think: Oh, this was the bit I first looked at. And it said: Donna is suspended in a massive cobweb in a ceiling wearing a wedding dress and I remember thinking; Well, this is something new, isn’t it?
  4. On the level of enthusiasm of the show: No.No.No. Didn’t know anything about it. In fact I actually don’t think I realised actually till last year quite how popular this show is. I certainly had no idea that my character got…” 
  5. On the conventions: I’ve certainly experienced things at conventions that I have not experienced…there is a level of intensity that I hadn’t expected. I think you are sort of shocked and you know, delighted but amazed at as well. Cause I had to really kind of remember stuff cause I don’t even remember what I was wearing on the show. And then people come up and say: ‘Do you recognise this?’ and you go; Why would I recognise that? And it’s cause they are wearing something I wore and now I know. I mean, I suppose the wedding dress gave it away a little bit but it still didn’t occur to me that they were dressing as me… It’s a delightful thing to be a spectator at, cause I think I am spectator at those events. 
  6. On her maybe being a Whovian?: *She laughs* I don’t think I have. I mean I do genuinely feel that I am part of something tho. But I just don’t know what…I don’t think I know the depths of what I’m part of cause they talk about things I don’t know.

title: Catherine Tate describing Doctor Who
body:
First impressions: 

It was…Well. The only episode I watched, because as I said it wasn’t my thing. No, I have seen it. It was like, tin foil and stuff or something. And I remember, you know ‘tuuuu tuuu’ you know the theme tune and a man with a scarf and Jelly babies or something and Daleks. So I knew, but. And I knew there was a show called Doctor Who, of course I did.

After being part of Doctor Who:

I know its about aliens and stuff. But you know, its more about the relationships I think. That’s what I thought it was about. 

But I am very amazed at how much people connect with it and they really do. And I don’t take that lightly. How much people love the show!

summary: thereareangels replied to your post  “I was secretly hoping for Americons news. But more talk about a Nan...” Can we discuss the...
body:
thereareangels replied to your post “I was secretly hoping for Americons news. But more talk about a Nan…”

Can we discuss the podcast though? Like the whole thing? because I just listened to it and I - AM - pUMPED!!

<sits back with a cup of tea>

I am too! Let’s talk.

How she got the name “Tate.” Soap was one of the funniest, smartest, ahead-of-its-time gems and I love that Catherine was so inspired by (the red haired!!!) Jessica Tate’s name.

Her way of coping with being bullied was to control how people viewed her. That’s rather brilliant.

Her approach to the “gladiator nature” of stand up comedy. You can see it in her panels, which don’t feature hecklers (can you IMAGINE!), how amazing she is on her feet and interacting with people. She’s natural, and it was fun to hear where that came from.

Her show coming into being, first a deep cut on the BBCs line-up to an overnight sensation.  It was a sudden shift, and she handled it with grace.

Donna. We knew she didn’t think people remembered/liked/cared about Donna, and it was sweet to hear David quickly denounce that and how happy she is to encounter fans, even if it was an education on how, um, devoted we are.

The fact that her life and career are so private, David, her friend, still got some of the details wrong in her early stages!!

Their adorable giggling. His awe in meeting someone who coined a new word (and she’s not too fussed about it!).  

“not only is my glass half empty, it’s not what I ordered and it’s chipped” - CATHERINE!!! (hugs)

body:
Can we appreciate that little thing the Tenth Doctor does when yelling? 

“AND I’M NOT LISTENING-AH!”

I just find it an interesting quirk in the way David Tennant portrayed 10, but it probably has more to do with him trying to keep the British accent while yelling.
